equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic core context drives branched-chain selection with I/V competition
equation_narrative.story: Position 61 in ubiquitin sits in a hydrophobic core environment, surrounded by 5 structural contacts that the model reads extensively in layers 8-22. The representation character remains consistently hydrophobic throughout perception, with leucine (L) dominating the logit lens at 47% by layer 23 due to its strong match with the hydrophobic context. The decision phase begins at layer 27 when isoleucine-specific prediction channels activate, driven by MLP neurons that distinguish I from L based on subtle packing constraints. Valine remains a strong competitor throughout, reflecting the model's recognition that any branched-chain hydrophobic residue fits this environment, with the final 50/46 I/V split indicating genuine biochemical ambiguity.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a clear hydrophobic core context through structural attention. Five structural contacts are read, with layer 20 head 4 showing 99% structural attention (though it acts as an eraser with -3.0 projection). Early features (F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 at 45+ projection) encode local sequence identity. By layer 9, the representation consolidates around hydrophobic character, with F9:5728 (49.5 proj) and related features establishing the buried, nonpolar environment. The logit lens reflects this context: alanine peaks at 21% (layer 12), leucine rises to 47% (layer 23), and valine maintains 12-17% throughout—all consistent with a hydrophobic core representation. Layer 18 features (F18:9851 at 19.5 proj, F18:4103 at 17.1 proj) encode structural environment rather than specific amino acid predictions.
perception_phase.context_character: Buried hydrophobic core environment with 5 structural contacts. The representation is strongly hydrophobic-leaning, consistent with branched-chain aliphatic residues (I, V, L) that pack efficiently in protein interiors. Minimal co-evolutionary signal (only 1 coevolving position) suggests local packing constraints dominate over long-range functional coupling.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 5 residues within contact distance, read by attention heads in L8-22 (L20 H4 shows 99% structural attention)
Hydrophobic context encoding: F9:5728 (49.5 proj), F9:1281 (45.3 proj) establish nonpolar character
Minimal co-evolution: only 1 coevolving position detected, indicating local packing dominates
Layer 18 structural features: F18:9851 (19.5 proj), F18:4103 (17.1 proj) encode burial and secondary structure context

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at layer 27 when isoleucine surges from 9% to 37%, overtaking leucine. MLP neurons in layers 27-31 drive this shift: N27:1236 (0.65 proj for I), N29:1215 (0.89 proj for I), and N31:4572 (0.89 proj for I) act as I-specific writers. Valine simultaneously strengthens through complementary neurons (N29:1180 votes equally for I and V at 0.61 each), creating the final 50/46 competition. Layer 30 attention (H6 with 2.57 proj, 29% structural attention) and layer 31 attention (H8 with 1.76 proj, 81% structural attention) provide late structural refinement that distinguishes I from L based on beta-branching geometry.
decision_phase.transition: Layer 24 marks the perception-to-decision boundary: F24:459 (17.3 proj) is the first high-projection feature, though still relatively generic. Layer 27 is the true commitment point—leucine collapses from 53% (layer 25) to 37% (layer 27) as I-specific MLP neurons activate. The representation shifts from encoding 'hydrophobic core residue' to actively selecting between I, V, and L based on packing geometry.

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine emerges decisively at layer 27 (rising from 9% to 37%) when I-specific MLP neurons activate. N27:1236 (0.65 proj), N29:1215 (0.89 proj), and N31:4572 (0.89 proj) form a consistent I-voting coalition across layers 27-31. Layer 30 features F30:7742 (40.5 proj) and F30:4107 (32.8 proj) provide attention-stream support. Isoleucine peaks at 83% (layer 32) before valine's late surge brings the final margin to 50/46, reflecting genuine biochemical ambiguity between these beta-branched hydrophobics.
key_evidence: N29:1215 (0.89 proj) — strongest I-specific MLP writer
F30:7742 (40.5 proj, attn) — I-supporting attention feature
L31 H8 (1.76 proj, 81% structural attn) — structural refinement favoring I

candidates.narrative: Valine maintains steady support throughout (12-17% in perception phase) and surges in the final layers, rising from 29% (layer 29) to 46% (layer 33). N29:1180 votes equally for I and V (0.61 proj each), and N30:1772 slightly favors V (0.53 proj for V vs 0.53 for I). The late surge is driven by layer 33 attention features: F33:6423 (106.3 proj), F33:5222 (102.9 proj), and F33:7165 (98.4 proj) all support V as an alternative branched-chain hydrophobic. The final 46% probability reflects that V is biochemically nearly equivalent to I in this buried core context.
candidates.key_layers: Steady 12-17% through L23, surges L29-33 to 45.7%
key_evidence: N29:1180 (0.61 proj for both I and V) — recognizes I/V equivalence

candidates.narrative: Leucine dominates the logit lens from layer 11 to layer 26, peaking at 53% (layer 25), because the representation character through perception is 'hydrophobic core residue' and L is the most common hydrophobic in protein cores. This is NOT the model predicting L—it's the representation's hydrophobic character projecting through the unembedding. L collapses at layer 27 (to 37%) when I-specific decision neurons activate, falling to 3.8% by layer 29 as the model commits to beta-branched residues (I/V) over linear-chain L.

candidates.narrative: Alanine appears prominently in early logit lens (20% at layer 0, peaks 21% at layer 12) because the representation initially encodes 'small hydrophobic' character before structural context fully resolves. This is a representation artifact—alanine is the simplest hydrophobic, so partial hydrophobic representations project toward A. As structural features accumulate (layers 13-18), the representation refines to 'buried, larger hydrophobic' and alanine fades to 3.4% (layer 23), then 0.2% (layer 33) as the model recognizes the position requires a bulkier residue for core packing.

N12:4911 (-0.19 proj) and N13:2090 (-0.21 proj) erase A as context refines
Structural features L18+ encode burial requiring larger sidechains
Final 0.2% shows A incompatible with resolved packing constraints

turning_points.description: The representation refines from 'generic hydrophobic' to 'buried core hydrophobic requiring larger sidechain.' Alanine drops from 21% to 8% as structural features emerge (F18:9851 at 19.5 proj, F18:4103 at 17.1 proj encode burial). MLP neurons in L12-L14 act as erasers: N12:4911 (-0.19 proj), N14:1115 (-0.52 proj) remove small/polar candidates. The logit lens shifts from A-dominant to L-dominant, reflecting the representation's evolution from 'small hydrophobic' to 'large hydrophobic core residue.'

The decisive commitment to beta-branched residues occurs here. Leucine collapses from 53% (L25) to 3.7% (L29) as I-specific MLP neurons fire: N27:1236 (0.65 proj), N29:1215 (0.89 proj). Isoleucine surges from 9% to 59% while valine rises from 12% to 29%. Layer 27 MLP contributes +1.45 total projection toward I, and layer 28 attention adds +1.74. This is where the model distinguishes beta-branched geometry (I/V) from linear-chain (L) based on packing constraints read from structural contacts.

Valine mounts a late challenge, rising from 29% (L29) to 46% (L33) while isoleucine drops from its 83% peak (L32) to 50%. Layer 31 MLP adds +1.41 total projection with N31:4572 (0.89 proj for I) competing against V-supporting neurons. Layer 33 attention delivers +8.34 total delta (+3.69 from attention), with features F33:6423 (106.3 proj) and F33:5222 (102.9 proj) supporting both I and V. The final 50/46 split reflects genuine biochemical ambiguity—both beta-branched hydrophobics fit this core environment nearly equally well.

deep_dives.caption: N27:1236 (0.65 proj for I), N29:1215 (0.89 proj for I), and N29:1180 (0.61 proj for both I and V) drive the beta-branched selection. Watch N21:1504 (-0.56 proj) and N26:859 (0.69 proj but votes L>I) for the L-to-I transition. Layer 28 shows strong I-writers: N28:2556 (0.47 proj), N28:936 (0.47 proj).

deep_dives.caption: N31:4572 (0.89 proj for I, 0.44 for V) and N31:1087 (0.63 proj for I) push isoleucine, while N31:3538 (-1.00 proj) erases non-hydrophobics. This layer sets up the final I/V competition by strongly supporting both beta-branched candidates.

deep_dives.caption: Layer 30 attention features (F30:7742 at 40.5 proj, F30:4107 at 32.8 proj) support I. Layer 33 features (F33:6423 at 106.3 proj, F33:5222 at 102.9 proj) drive the late V surge. These are true prediction channels with high amino-acid specificity, unlike the context-encoding features in early layers.

deep_dives.label: Velocity events L27-L29
deep_dives.caption: Layer 27 shows -2.96 total delta (MLP-driven, away from I as L collapses). Layer 28 shows +3.21 total delta (both attn and MLP, toward I). Layer 29 is not in top velocity events but delivers the decisive I surge to 59%. This sequence shows the L→I transition mechanics.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts isoleucine by assembling a hydrophobic core context from 5 structural contacts and recognizing that this buried environment requires a beta-branched hydrophobic residue. The decision hinges on layers 27-29, where MLP neurons (N27:1236, N29:1215 with 0.65-0.89 proj) distinguish I from the leucine that dominated perception-phase logit lens. The final 50/46 I/V split reflects genuine biochemical ambiguity—both beta-branched hydrophobics satisfy the packing constraints equally well. The model's confidence (49.9%) is appropriately modest given this near-equivalence, and the correct prediction demonstrates successful integration of local sequence, structural contacts, and geometric packing constraints.
